[3] Kansas
Date: Fri 16 Mar 2018
Source: WIBW [edited]
http://www.wibw.com/content/news/More-measles-found-in-Johnson-Miami-Co-477138393.html?ref=393


The Kansas Dept. of Health and Environment says the agency has received 6 additional cases of the infectious disease within days of learning of one at a Johnson Co. daycare. Five of the new reports come from Johnson Co., while the other one is just to the south, in Miami Co.

Some of the new cases reportedly appeared outside the daycare, and KDHE is worried people in the general population may have been exposed.

"Measles is spread through the air by breathing, coughing or sneezing," said KDHE Chief Health Officer, Dr. Greg Lakin. "It is so contagious that any person who is exposed to it, and is not immune, will likely contract the disease."

So far, KDHE says they and Johnson Co. have figured out where each individual was infected and are working to identify the contacts. They warn if someone has been to one of the listed locations, that person may have been exposed [see URL for locations of possible exposure].

On average, a person won't start showing symptoms for the measles for 10-14 days, and it may take up to 3 weeks before they do. If someone starts showing symptoms and plans to go see a healthcare provider, they are urged to call ahead so the facility can take measures to protect other patients and staff.

KDHE described measles as a respiratory disease. Initial symptoms typically are high fever, cough, runny nose, and red watery eyes. After about 3 to 5 days a rash begins to develop. It usually starts around the hairline and spreads down the neck, trunk, arms, and legs.

Health officials remind everyone the best way to protect themselves is to get the MMR vaccination.

[Byline: Nick Viviani]

