[13] Brazil
Date: Mon 12 Mar 2018
Source: Roraim [machine trans. edited]
https://g1.globo.com/rr/roraima/noticia/onze-novos-casos-suspeitos-de-sarampo-sao-registrados-em-48h-em-roraima.ghtml


The number of reported cases of measles in Roraima has reached 50 since the 1st case, on 13 Feb 2018, was identified in Boa Vista. Only on this weekend, during Sat 10 Mar and Sun 11 Mar 2018, 11 new suspected cases were registered. So far, 14 patients have had the confirmed diagnosis of the disease in every state, and 36 remain under investigation.

The updated data were released on Mon 14 Mar 2018 by the State Department of Health (Sesau). All confirmed cases were recorded in Venezuelans ranging in age from 7 months-18 years.

The general coordinator of Health Surveillance, Daniela Souza, explained that all 11 new suspects were admitted with symptoms of measles in health units.

Of these, 7 were recorded in Warao Indians in the municipality of Pacaraima, a city bordering Venezuela. These were the earliest records of the disease outside the capital.

Most of the patients are people who have recently arrived from Venezuela, according to the coordinator general. The age range of notified patients varies from 3-month-old infants to 33-year-old adults.

On Saturday [10 Mar 2018], the 'Dia [Day] D' vaccination against measles was carried out in Roraima . Two days after the campaign, Sesau said he had not yet counted how many people had been immunized throughout the state.

According to the municipality of Boa Vista, 20 431 people were reached in the municipality, of which 9693 were already vaccinated. Only 10 601 who did not have the vaccine received the dose.

The vaccination campaign was brought forward across the state to prevent an outbreak of the disease. The expectation is that by 10 Apr 2018, 420 000 Venezuelans and Brazilians will be immunized.

Since 2015, Roraima has received an increasing influx of Venezuelan immigrants. The city of Boa Vista estimates that they already have 40 000 living in the capital. Many come to the state in search of food and work, but others are also in need of medical care.

The 1st suspected case of measles was recorded in a Venezuelan immigrant baby on 13 Feb 2018. The patient lived with her family in a square in the center of Boa Vista.

An analysis made by the Oswaldo Cruz Foundation (Fiocruz) has confirmed that the virus circulating in the state originated in Venezuela. Before the campaign, about 2000 immigrants had already been immunized in the streets, squares and shelters of the state.

[Byline: Inaê Brandao]

